Primitives and strings can be changed inside a method, but only if they were created outside the method. For example:

int x = 1;

void foo(int x){x = 3;}

void bar(int y){x = 5;}

A call to foo will not change the global variable x, because x is declared in the argument, so there is a local x within the method. When x = 3; is called, it is this local variable x which gets assigned the value 3.

A call to bar will change the global variable x, because there is no declaration of x within the method, so when it gets to the instruction, the program will look up the chain until it finds a variable x, which in this case is the global one.  That value is the one that gets reassigned to 5.

The array differs because the elements within the global array will be changed even if there is a declaration of the array variable within the method.

Dear JimRyals,

both Yeechian and Jon-286 are right.

The point here is that you are only allowed to change a variable if it is in your scope.

When we code:

<pre>
void foo(int x){
  x = x+15;
}
</pre>
And we call (from another function)
<pre>
int x = 10;
foo(x);
</pre>

These 2 x variables are different. So, x is not changed outside foo.

When you pass a parameter to a function it is copied in the stack of the function (a special part of the memory). You are changing a copy of the original variable. Although they have the same name, they are actually different variables that are stored in different memory addresses. 

With arrays (and later objects) is different.


When you do
<pre>
int array[] = new int[4];

array[0] = 10;
array[1] = 11;
array[2] = 12;
array[3] = 13;
</pre>

The variable name <code>array</code> stores the memory address where the actual 10, the 11, the 12, the 13 are allocated. So, <code>array</code> is a reference (a pointer, if you want). The name of the array is the location where you can find the actual values.

When you do
<pre>
void foo(int[] array){
  for (int i = 0; i< array.length; i++){
      array[i] = 12;
  }
}


foo(array);
</pre>

The method receives a copy of the value of the position (the memory address) where the array is allocated. So, you know where the array is stored and you are allowed to change it. Because you are accessing to the values through their addresses.

Why all this?

The special section of memory (the stack) has a size limit for each function. If you need to pass an array of 250000 integers, you can overflow the stack (and the process of copying all these values to the stack will take a lot of time). 

Instead of that, we copy in the stack only where the array is allocated (the memory address of the array) that, depending on the architecture of the machine will be 4 or 8 bytes (the length of a memory address), much less than 250000 * size of an int = 250000 * 4 bytes.

