After pressing run, the application runs continuously and so does any method called from within the **act**() method's body. So, if you try to change the behavior of the **playSound**() method by changing alternately the state of a designated (auxiliary) variable, you'll get the job done for just one cycle. In other words: **playSound**() will be called as long as the "**h**" key is pressed. If "**h**" is pressed more than few seconds, the application will crash. 

To avoid this, the second key ("**j**" in the following example) is needed for changing the state of the auxiliary variable, assuming the latter was initialised with "false" and then set on "true" when "**h**" key was pressed.

    /**
     * Activates the car's horn once, when the key "h" is pressed, then deactivates the horn
     * Reactivates the car's horn after pressing key "j"
     */
    public void useCarHorn()
    {
        if(Greenfoot.isKeyDown("h")){
            if(isHornActivated == true){
                try{
                    Greenfoot.playSound("");
                }
                catch(java.lang.IllegalArgumentException exp){
                }
            }
            else{
                isHornActivated = true;
                Greenfoot.playSound("42670858.wav");
            }
        }
        if(Greenfoot.isKeyDown("j")){
            isHornActivated = false;
        }

    }

