Well, I have managed to pass this exam with a solid 87% or 13 out of 15 correct answers. Anyway, I think the graders owe me one more point, because I think that the correct answer to question regarding "Number of times that sentences are executed" is the second choice "II only".

    void bar(int[] array, int num, int lim){
        int i = 0;
        int v = 0;
        while ((i < array.length) && (array[i] + num < lim)){
            if (array[i] <= array[v]){
                v = i; /* Statement A */
            }  
            i++; /* Statement B */
        }
        System.out.println(v);
    }

Namely, for the second half of the while loop condition (array[i] + num < lim) to yield true when lim=8 numbers in the array must be less than 6 if we take the smallest possible value for "num". On the other hand, the numbers in the array must increase, with only three of them being equal or sorted in descending order, if we want Statement A to be executed exactly three times.
So, in order for the "II and III only" to be the correct answer, we would have to have an ascending sequence of 10 natural numbers (because Statement B has to be executed 10 times), but we only have to use numbers from 1 to 6, which is impossible.
The best case scenario for option III from the table to be possible is that the param values be:

lim = 8 (given value)
num = 1
array {1,1,1,2,3,4,5,6}

because this would yield three Executions of Statement A, but **only eight** Executions of Statement B.

So, in my opinion, the correct answer for the question of " Number of times that sentences are executed" is "II only". For that reason, I would ask the admins to revise my overall score for this exam! :)

